Scotland’s independent schools have improved academic achievement records, failing to deliver in 2018, and have once again demonstrated exceptional exam results that have only been further enhanced by individual and collective achievements in the fields of sport, art, music, and other communities from across the nation.
With more than 30,000 students in total across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), aim to provide the highest level of service to their students and their parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for further and higher education, for their chosen careers and to be citizens of the world.
Working in the education sector, which can design and implement a school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be popular and are willingly chosen in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you can speak to a man in a language he understands, he will understand you with his mind.
If you speak to him in his own language, you will speak to his heart.”
This is a strong reminder that we cannot rely solely on English if we want to knit relationships and build trust with people from other countries.
According to the results of this year’s final exams, we can say that languages are at the top of popularity and have the best retention ratings in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of foreign language learners received the highest A-rating.
The data collected from 74 schools that are members of SCIS showed that 72% of students received the highest grade of A during the Mandarin language exam, the highest grade of A received 72% of the German language learners, as well as the highest grade of A received by 69% of the students.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland consider foreign language teaching to be an essential skill that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages, as an elective subject, are now considered as important as the major subjects (science, technology, engineering, and mathematics) in independent school programs and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK’s Employment and Skills Commission found that, for all the reasons that made it difficult for employers to fill jobs, 17 percent lacked language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly mandatory for young people to be ready for their future careers.
As employment opportunities will be highly dependent on languages in the future, these skills are becoming essential in a globalised world.
No matter what career a person chooses when paying for a second language, in the future he will be far superior to others if he has the skills needed throughout his life.
Being able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries, a person who learns several languages will be much more competitive.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 UK adults, 75 per cent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to participate in the conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage of people, i.e. 15 per cent.
That’s why investing in language learning is important for today’s children.
By paying for several languages, especially in developing countries, children will have better opportunities for meaningful employment.
In Scotland, every school is different in the languages they are taught.
A number of schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered the most important in the UK, looking to the future of 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interests may be, there will always be plenty of languages to choose from in an independent school with teaching staff and professionals in the field.
Scottish independent schools are ready to create a learning environment that will prepare children and give them the skills they need to live in the future.
There is no denying that in today’s global business environment, languages remain vital to the future of the country, which is why it is necessary to reflect this in the education system as well.
Indeed, modern languages should certainly be considered “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this opportunity to choose, diversity and results to young people in Scotland.
This needs to be done.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
