North Korea says it will not arm itself unilaterally if it can't be trusted
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions were deepening their distrust of the United States and that under such circumstances the country would certainly not unilaterally give up nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho told the General Assembly that North Korea had taken "significant measures of good will" in recent years, such as halting nuclear missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test base, and committing not to deploy nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
“We have not received a response from the United States,” he said.
"Without any confidence in the United States, we will not be able to rely on our national security, and under such circumstances, we will not be the first to unilaterally arm ourselves."
While Ri reiterated North Korea’s already-heard complaints about Washington’s opposition to the phased approach to nuclear disarmament, under which North Korea would be compensated in stages for its actions, his statement stood out in that he did not completely reject the idea of bilateral disarmament as a form of disarmament.
Ri referred to a joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first meeting of the US president and North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work on “the disarmament of the Korean peninsula,” and Trump pledged to ensure North Korea’s security.
North Korea is seeking a formal end to the 1950-1953 Korean War, but the United States says Pyongyang must first abandon its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also refused to ease tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“The U.S. demands nuclear disarmament first and is increasing the pressure of sanctions to achieve its goal by means of coercive methods, even by renouncing the declaration of an end to the war,” Ri said.
“To think that sanctions can knock us out is the same as giving birth to utopian dreams for people we don’t care about.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions deepen our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second meeting between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. leader stressed earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months: "If the other country was South Korea on the issue of nuclear disarmament, not the United States, the issue of the Korean Peninsula nuclear disarmament would not have taken such an action."
However, Ri’s tone of speech changed dramatically compared to last year when he told the UN General Assembly that when “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim a “missile master” preparing a suicide mission, directing a North Korean missile into the United States was completely impossible.
At the United Nations this year, Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, rallied to Kim for the courage to take steps toward disarmament, but said there was still much to be done and that sanctions must remain until North Korea’s claim to maturity.
Trump said on Wednesday that there was no timetable for that, saying "if it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter."
China and Russia have said that the UN Security Council should compensate Pyongyang for the actions it has taken.
But U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that "the Security Council's sanctions must be resolutely continued without any rebates until the full and definitive evidence-based nuclear disarmament is carried out."
The Security Council has voted in favour of sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to prevent the financing of Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri at the back of the UN General Assembly and later said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to clear the ground for another meeting.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but the last trip was unsuccessful.
In July, he left Pyongyang, saying that all the progress was only for North Korea to announce after a few hours that he had made “gangster demands.”
North Korea, during a meeting with Moon this month, promised to dismantle the missile base and nuclear complex if the United States takes "appropriate measures".
Kim said the “appropriate measures” he sought were security assurances Trump had promised in Singapore and a move to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard students learn to get enough rest.
A new course at Harvard University this year encouraged all of its students to sleep more in order to combat the growing macho culture in studies, by consuming caffeine and not sleeping at night.
One academic found that at the best university in the world, students often don’t even have a basic knowledge of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and Brigham City, a specialist in women's hospitals, has developed a course that he says is the first of its kind in the United States.
Inspiration to prepare this course visited him after talking about the impact of lack of sleep on learning.
“At the end of the speech, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why am I only being told about this now, in the last year of my studies?’
She said that no one had told her about the importance of sleep, and that surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course is offered for the first time this year. It explains to students how the most important habits of quality sleep help to achieve academic and sports results, improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University’s Department of Health Services, said the university decided to offer this course when it turned out that students were very sleep-deprived during the week.
The one-hour course covers a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is a photo of the dorm room, where students can click on a coffee cup, curtains, trainers and books and thus learn about the effects of caffeine, light, how lack of sleep affects the results of sports and what is the importance of walking to sleep routine.
In the next section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A student town map with interactive icons that encourage participants to think about their daily routines.
“We understand that this will not immediately change the behavior of students.
But we think they have a right to know – just like you have a right to know about the health consequences when you choose to smoke,” explained Professor Czeisler.
A culture of pride not to sleep at night, according to him, still exists. Modern technology and increasing pressure on students have led to the growing problem of lack of sleep.
“Ensuring that you get enough and quality sleep should be the student’s secret weapon in combating stress, exhaustion and anxiety,” he said, “even while avoiding weight gain because lack of sleep switches the brain to starvation mode, so students are constantly feeling hungry.”
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler prepare a course when he attended one of his subjects at Harvard last year.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to apply for a course available to the entire student campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to invite all second-cycle students to listen to this course before starting to visit this competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended students to set an alarm clock when it’s time to go to sleep, just like the one that wakes up, and to guard against the harmful effects of blue light emitted by electronic devices and light-emitting diodes because they can knock your circadian rhythm out of balance.
